docs.abstract: Georgia has allowed its residents to arrest one another since 1863. But after the shooting death of Ahmaud Arbery, critics are calling for such laws to be repealed.

docs.lead_paragraph: After Ahmaud Arbery was shot dead by two white men on a quiet residential road in coastal Georgia, a prosecutor cited a Civil War era state law to justify the killing.

headline.main: The Citizen’s Arrest Law Cited in Arbery’s Killing Dates Back to the Civil War

docs.lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — A South Georgia resident’s video of the killing of Ahmaud Arbery helped spark nationwide protests and revive law enforcement scrutiny of the case, resulting in murder charges against two men who chased and fatally shot Mr. Arbery.

docs.lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — Three shots were fired in the confrontation that killed Ahmaud Arbery, a 25-year-old black man who was chased by white men as he ran through their southeastern Georgia neighborhood. The authorities said Travis McMichael, who with his father and a neighbor pursued Mr. Arbery, pulled the trigger.

headline.main: Investigators Say One Man Shot Ahmaud Arbery. Why Are Three Charged With Murder?
headline.print_headline: Investigators Say One Man Shot Arbery. Why Are 3 Charged With Murder?

docs.lead_paragraph: President Trump issued a violent ultimatum to protesters in Minneapolis on Friday and inserted himself in a harshly divisive fashion into the crisis there, attacking the city’s Democratic mayor and raising the specter that the military could use armed force to suppress riots that erupted after the death of George Floyd, a black man, at the hands of a white police officer.

docs.lead_paragraph: Welcome to the weekend. It’s been a hard week. The United States reached a grim milestone, and as we move into the weekend, the streets are on fire in Minneapolis as people protest the death of George Floyd. Here are some great articles you may have missed if you had to tune out a bit this week for your own well-being. So take a walk or get some coffee and settle in for some amazing journalism.

docs.abstract: Brunswick, Ga., gained national attention during the civil rights era for the way black and white leaders had worked together to integrate peacefully.
docs.snippet: Brunswick, Ga., gained national attention during the civil rights era for the way black and white leaders had worked together to integrate peacefully.
docs.lead_paragraph: BRUNSWICK, Ga. — A 26-year-old black man stood on the steps of the old brick courthouse on Friday and decried the shooting death of another black man who would have turned 26 that day had he lived to see it. “That could have easily been me,” he said.

headline.main: In Ahmaud Arbery’s Hometown, Pain, Anger and Pride in a Shared Racial History
headline.print_headline: In a Georgia Killing, Pain and Anger, But Also a History of Racial Harmony
